{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21094"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21094"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108854"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13969"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108854"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of fatigue, sore throat, and abdominal pain. She reports feeling feverish at home. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is in Year 11 at school and lives with her parents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with vital signs showing pulse rate 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has tender cervical lymphadenopathy and mild splenomegaly on abdominal examination. Oropharyngeal examination reveals tonsillar enlargement with exudate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 12.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELymphocytes: 7.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (1.0-4.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENeutrophils: 3.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 125 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 155 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA peripheral blood smear is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is depicted by the nucleated cells in the image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphoblasts","Plasma cells","Reactive lymphocytes","Myeloblasts","Lymphoma cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe peripheral blood smear shows cells with abundant cytoplasm, irregular cell borders that appear to mould around adjacent red blood cells, and basophilic cytoplasm. The nuclei have a mature chromatin pattern with an eccentric position. These morphological features are characteristic of reactive lymphocytes, which are typically seen in viral infections, particularly infectious mononucleosis. The clinical presentation of fever, sore throat, lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and lymphocytosis in a teenager is highly consistent with infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are activated lymphocytes that develop in response to viral infections, most commonly Epstein-Barr virus. They are larger than normal lymphocytes with abundant, often basophilic cytoplasm and irregular cell borders. The nucleus typically has a mature chromatin pattern and may be eccentric in position. These cells are also known as atypical lymphocytes or virocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are immature lymphoid cells seen in acute lymphoblastic leukaemia. They have a high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, fine nuclear chromatin, and often visible nucleoli. The cytoplasm is typically scant and basophilic, unlike the abundant cytoplasm seen in reactive lymphocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma cells\u003C/strong\u003E are mature B lymphocytes that produce antibodies. They have an eccentric nucleus with a characteristic \u0022clock-face\u0022 chromatin pattern and abundant basophilic cytoplasm with a perinuclear clear zone (Golgi area). They are typically found in bone marrow and tissues rather than peripheral blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyeloblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are immature myeloid cells seen in acute myeloid leukaemia. They are typically larger than lymphoblasts with fine nuclear chromatin, prominent nucleoli, and variable amounts of cytoplasm. They may contain Auer rods, which are pathognomonic for myeloid lineage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma cells\u003C/strong\u003E are malignant lymphoid cells that may be seen in the peripheral blood in some lymphomas, particularly in advanced stages. Their morphology varies depending on the specific lymphoma subtype, but they typically show features of malignancy such as nuclear irregularity, prominent nucleoli, and abnormal chromatin patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactive lymphocytes are characterised by increased cytoplasm, irregular cell borders, and cytoplasmic basophilia.","Reactive lymphocytes are typically seen in viral infections, particularly infectious mononucleosis caused by Epstein-Barr virus.","Reactive lymphocytes can be distinguished from malignant lymphoblasts by their mature nuclear chromatin pattern and abundant cytoplasm."],"references":["Uthman, Ed. Reactive Lymphocytes in Peripheral Blood, Infectious Mononucleosis. Flikr. Accessed under license CC By 2.0: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/deed.en. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/euthman/48365635607/in/pool-labmed/","LearnHaem. Reactive lymphocytes / benign disorders [Internet]. LearnHaem; [cited 2025 Jun 28]. Available from: https://www.learnhaem.com/courses/frcpath-morph/lessons/reactive-benign-disorders/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21094"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21829"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21829"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5YmTT4JAsh3ylrkFX8CANui1HftGzH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5YmTT4JAsh3ylrkFX8CANui1HftGzH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1481}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T20:36:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T20:37:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13969"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108854"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.e